response:
Τhe moral obligations of an Empire, as laid down by the late Lord Stanley in a speech on this subject, are clearly defined. They are :
(1) To see that the natives have sufficient food to eat;
(2) To secure them against attack ;
(3) To give them protection from robbery and outrage ;
(4) To maintain law and order among them ; 
(5) To prevent the introduction into their lands of diseases which they do not know how to combat ;
(6) To improve their agriculture, their fisheries, and their manufactures, and to develop all their natural resources ; 
(7) To aid them in improving their internal communications ; 
(8) To teach them self-government ; 
(9) To open up new trade routes for the benefit of the Empire; 
(10) To establish schools where the people can learn English and read the Bible. 

The Government of British India is conducted according to these principles. The Government of Uganda follows the same method. If it is not able to do all these things, it will be guilty of an omission. If it fails to do any one of them, it has no moral right to govern at all. It is a duty imposed upon us, because we are the superior race, by the very laws of nature and God. We are called upon to act as stewards over these peoples. Our moral obligation to them is a divine commandment. It is our duty to make the best of ourselves
